Making yachts during the coronavirus lockdown. I have a friend named Pete who makes yachts for a living. Pete was quite worried about the virus as he thought not many people would be in the market for one of his nice boats. His yachts are big, sturdy, and beautiful, but primarily they're designed for big groups of people. Who's going to want to ride a yacht during a time of social distancing? Plus these bad boys cost a pretty penny, during times of economic uncertainty it seemed unlikely people will be looking to splash out on a shiny new yacht. Then in mid-March it got even worse, they had to close his factory due to the lockdown. How on earth is he going to make money now? He has 5 kids to feed not to mention the horse farm he just invested in! Well Pete has always been a man of impeccable determination and entrepreneurial spirit, so he brought his bows, sterns, sales, helms, cleats, bliges, and hulls home with him and began working from his garage. At the beginning it was very difficult as he was used to building yachts in a team, however with some hard work and perseverance he was churning them out in no time. 1 yacht. 2 yachts. 3 yachts. Soon the word broke out and people were so inspired by his story that they started buying his boats! It started off rough but this looks like it's going to be his most profitable year ever. So when you're thinking about the doom and gloom of lockdown, just remember its not bad for everybody: my mate Pete makes yachts in his garage, and his sales went through the roof.
